<header>
<h1 class="blog--title">This Year in Spring - December 31, 2013</h1>
<div class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item desktop-only">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon engineering"></div>
<a class="category">Engineering</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<img class="meta-data--icon" src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/fb22593caf24e4bb4c98d467cdd247e6?s=20&amp;d=mm" />
<a class="author" rel="author" href="/team/jlong">Josh Long</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2013-12-31 19:54:00.0">December 31, 2013</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="1333" href="/blog/2013/12/31/this-year-in-spring-december-31-2013#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</div>
</header>
<div class="blog--post"><p>Happy New Year! Welcome back to this year&rsquo;s final installment of <em>This Week in Spring</em>! </p><p>We&rsquo;ll do some of the news, as usual, and then I&rsquo;ll take a look back over the last year in news surrounding Spring, of which there&rsquo;s been much indeed!</p>
<ol>
<li>Matt Raible, who we know has also been looking at Spring Boot, <a href="http://www.infoq.com/news/2013/12/spring4">just wrote up our just-released Spring 4 for InfoQ</a>. Definitely worth a read if you have the time!</li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>Xavier Padró has a nice post on retrying web service operations with <a href="https://xpadro.blogspot.com/2013/12/retry-web-service-operations-with.html"><code>RequestHandlerRetryAdvice</code></a>.</li>
<li>There&rsquo;s a great discussion on Stack Overflow on Spring&rsquo;s <code>CrudRepository</code> vs. the more JPA-specific <code>JpaRepository</code> with an <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/14014086/what-is-difference-between-crudrepository-and-jparepository-interfaces-in-spring/20784007">awesome answer by Spring Data lead Oliver Gierke</a></li>
<li>Ken Blair has put together a nice introduction to doing bean mapping <a href="http://kenblair.net/orika-spring-easy-bean-mapping/">using the Orika bean-mapping framework alongside Spring</a></li>
<li>Groovy ninja Guillaume LaForge has started putting together a nice roundup of all the latest happenings in the Groovy community, and I&rsquo;d just like to invite readers of <a href="https://glaforge.appspot.com/article/groovy-weekly-2">this column to check out that series, as well</a></li>
<li>Viral Patel is back at it again, this time with a post on <a href="http://viralpatel.net/blogs/spring-requestheader-example/">handling request headers with Spring MVC</a></li>
<li>Norris Shelton, Jr. has put together a nice post on rendering validation messages from <a href="https://norrisshelton.wordpress.com/2013/12/30/getting-spring-mvc-validation-messages-from-a-json-service/">a JSON service with Spring MVC</a>.</li>
<li>Jim White on the <em>Intertech</em> blog has a post that looks at <a href="http://www.intertech.com/Blog/spring-4-generic-qualifiers/">Spring 4&rsquo;s generics-aware dependency injection</a>.</li>
<li>Lalit Jha has a nice post on how to <a href="https://spring-webservice-2-step-by-step.blogspot.com/2013/12/spring-framework-integration-with-play.html">integrate Play with Spring for dependency injection</a>. To be honest, I think I&rsquo;ve seen alternative approaches that were different, so apparently there are many ways to approach this. Interesting read, nonetheless!</li>
<li>Microsoft put up a little note <a href="https://blogs.msdn.com/b/windowsazurej/archive/2013/12/25/blog-migrating-a-java-spring-framework-application-to-windows-azure.aspx">on running Spring applications on Windows Azure</a>. I don&rsquo;t necessarily recommend Azure, but if you&rsquo;re going that route anyway&hellip; :)</li>
<li>The <em>numberformat</em> blog has a nice post (titled <em>the 3 r’s of spring batch 3.0.x with annotations</em>) on <a href="https://numberformat.wordpress.com/2013/12/28/the-3-rs-of-spring-batch-3-0-x-with-annotations/">using Spring Batch&rsquo;s Java Configuration API</a>. Definitely worth a read!</li>
<li>The <em>Way2Java</em> blog has a nice post <a href="http://way2java.com/spring/spring-aop-after-throwing-advice-example/">on using Spring AOP&rsquo;s after-throwing advice</a>.</li>
<li>Zheng Dongping (I&rsquo;m assuming that it&rsquo;s his blog, too, though I only saw this name in the <code>@author</code> attribution in the code&hellip; otherwise this blog&rsquo;s under the user <em>dempe</em>) put together a code-only look at how to <a href="https://www.cnblogs.com/dempe/p/3484190.html">use Spring Data MongoDB&rsquo;s mapping support</a>. The balance of the blog is in Chinese, so I was only relying on what Google Translate could give me. Looked good, though.</li>
<li><em>xinhuaxuan</em>, also under the same Chinese Blogs site as the former entry, put together a nice post <a href="https://www.cnblogs.com/xinhuaxuan/p/3490126.html">on using Spring&rsquo;s <code>@Required</code> annotation</a> to trigger startup-time checks for the presence of dependencies.</li>
</ul><p>Looking back over the past year and trying to summarize it is <em>very</em> difficult! Beleive me, I know, <a href="http://blog.gopivotal.com/products/have-you-seen-spring-lately">I&rsquo;ve tried</a> and <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_twyZL_AGCI">tried</a>! This year saw the Spring team join <a href="http://gopivotal.com">GoPivotal</a>, which in turn has led to one wild ride for all involved! Here, in short order, is some of the stuff that got our attention in <em>This Week in Spring</em>:</p>
<ol>
<li><a href="https://spring.io/blog/2013/12/12/announcing-spring-framework-4-0-ga-release">We launched Spring 4!</a> This featured markedly improved REST support, Java EE 7 and Java 8 support, websockets support, and a slew of other features.</li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>3..2&hellip; 1&hellip; Lift Off! We joined <a href="https://twitter.com/gopivotal">the GoPivotal initiative</a> at the end of March 2013! (and formally in various other countries in the months to follow)</li>
<li>At our annual <a href="http://springone2gx.com">SpringOne2GX</a> conference, we launched the new home of Spring on the web, <a href="https://spring.io/">Spring.IO</a>! (You probably already knew about it if you&rsquo;re reading this blog! :D )</li>
<li><a href="http://www.infoq.com/news/2013/06/cloudfoundry_v2">Cloud Foundry v2 was released</a></li>
<li>We launched <a href="http://www.gopivotal.com/press-center/11122013-pivotal-one">Pivotal One</a>, the comprehensive platform which features Pivotal HD and Cloud Foundry as well as popular infrastructure like <a href="https://rabbitmq.com">RabbitMQ</a>, <a href="http://redios.io">Redis</a>, etc., and of course <a href="https://spring.io">Spring</a> features at the heart of it all.</li>
<li>This year, of course, saw the release of many fine updates to the usual suspects including <a href="https://projects.spring.io/spring-social/">Spring Social</a> , <a href="https://projects.spring.io/spring-integration">Spring Integration</a>, <a href="https://projects.spring.io/spring-batch">Spring Batch</a>, <a href="https://projects.spring.io/spring-data">Spring Data</a>, <a href="https://projects.spring.io/spring-security">Spring Security</a> and <a href="https://projects.spring.io/spring-hadoop">Spring for Hadoop </a>. Notably: Spring Batch got a new Java Configuration API and saw its design underpin that of the just-released <a href="https://jcp.org/en/jsr/detail?id=352">Batch standard</a>. Spring Data added even more projects to the release train. Spring Integration 3.0 just shipped with numerous new adapters and improvements. Spring Security&rsquo;s Java configuration API and raft of improvements for open-web application security all hit this year.</li>
<li><a href="https://projects.spring.io/spring-boot">Spring Boot</a>, which takes an opinionated view of the Spring platform and third-party libraries so you can get started with minimum fuss, hit mid-year to rave reception and reviews. Spring Boot&rsquo;s been making waves all over the industry with Java developers and developers from other communities alike agreed: Boot is productive.</li>
<li><a href="https://projects.spring.io/spring-xd">Spring XD</a> delivers a turnkey appliance for building big-data aware applications. Spring XD, which builds on top of Spring Batcha and Spring Integration, is a <em>runtime</em>, and can handle common things like scaling a job by itself.</li>
<li>And, of course, any discussion about the great big-data technology coming out of Pivotal would be incomplete without mention of <a href="http://www.gopivotal.com/products/pivotal-hd/">Pivotal HD</a>, our enterprise-grade Hadoop distribution. Pivotal HD, of course, works well with Spring for Hadoop and is a natural data-warehousing complement to the online processing supported featured in <a href="https://projects.spring.io/spring-xd">Spring XD</a>.</li>
<li>While this list could continue ad nauseum, the most amazing aspect of 2013 was you, the community: world-wide, loud and proud, your code, blogs, articles, videos, talks at conferences, Tweets, and interactions have driven <em>This Week in Spring</em> through it all. Thanks, and rock on!</li>
</ul><p>I&rsquo;m sure I speak for all of the Spring team in wishing you the happiest, healthiest and safest of New Years (if you haven&rsquo;t already crossed it yet)! We&rsquo;ll see you in 2014! </p></div>
</div>
